Detailed design document & specification

Java 21 added virtual threads, which is a feature that fundamentally relies on JVM functionality that allows for call stacks to be paused, unmounted, and remounted. We can use that functionality ourselves - without needing all the virtual thread stuff - and use it to implement coroutines and async/await functionality for a command based framework.

Basically, it allows for commands to written almost like a normal function - standard Java control flow like if statements and while loops are possible and encouraged.

For example, a simple command in v2 that sets a motor until some setpoint target is reached, then turns off the motor would look like this:

Which needs knowledge of how command functions are handled (init, execute, end condition, completion/cleanup) and the DSL methods to do so.

In v3, the same command would just use a normal while loop with a coroutine to manage pausing and resuming - it must be cooperative multitasking - but otherwise is just normal Java code.

This is fairly similar between both frameworks because all the logic is in a periodic function. The only change is that V3 moves the logic to an explicit while loop with a yield call, while V2 relies on the scheduler running its body once per robot loop.

Moving an elevator to a specific reef level, then scoring a piece of coral. Note how v2 needs to make use of multiple proxies in an awkward parallel group at the start of the command, while v3 can just use the coroutine to fork them in a single function body. This is because the v3 scheduler keeps track of every running command, instead of having parallel and sequential groups manage their commands internally, allowing the scheduler to prevent inner commands from interrupting their parents.
